*Let's look at these principles:*

*1st. Principle of simplification and the single enemy:*

 Use simplification, not diversification, in choosing a single enemy. One must choose one enemy at a time: one must ignore what others do and concentrate on one until one is done with it. 

*2nd. Principle of contagion method:*

Disclose the contagion capacity that this enemy has.  Put a perfect before and show how the present and the future are being contaminated by this enemy.

*3rd. Principle of transposition:*

 One must transfer all social evils to this enemy, and if he cannot deny bad news, one must invent others to distract them. 

*4th. Principle of exaggeration and disfigurement:*

 One must exaggerate bad news to the point of disfiguring it, transforming a small or minor offense into a serious threat, into a thousand offenses, thus creating a climate of deep insecurity and fear. 

*5th. Principle of vulgarization:*

 The goal is to turn everything into something clumsy and bad-natured so that the actions of the enemy are understood as vulgar, ordinary, easy to discover. 

*6th. Principle of orchestration:*

 Propaganda must be limited to a small number of ideas that must be repeated tirelessly, presented over and over again from different perspectives, but always converging on the same concept. Rumors should be made to snore until they become news.

*7th. Principle of renewal:*

 New information and arguments must always be delivered at such a pace that by the time the opponent responds the audience is already interested in something else. The answers to the opponent should never overcome the growing level of accusations, a bombardment of news (about the chosen enemy) so that the receiver does not have time to think, as he is suffocated by them. 

*8th. Principle of verisimilitude:*

 It is necessary to build arguments from diverse sources or fragmented information in order to diversify opinions through expert interpretations, but all opinions against the chosen enemy. The goal is that the receiver does not realize that the interpreted subject is not true.

*9th. Principle of silence:*

 One should silence information about which one has no arguments and conceal or hide news that favors the opponent. It is important to hide all information that is not convenient.

*10th. Principle of transfer:*

The general rule of propaganda always operates from a pre-existing substrate, that is, a national mythology, a complex of hatreds, of traditional prejudices. 

*11th. Principle of unanimity:*

It seeks convergence on matters of general interest in order to seize the feeling of popular outcry against the chosen enemy. The feeling that is sought is that of unanimity, that â€œeveryone thinks soâ€. Here one reaches the common sense that operates the license to exercise the â€œexceptionâ€ against the enemy.
